---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';

const faq = [
  { question: "What is Ray Serve and how does it relate to Ray?", answer: "Ray Serve is the model serving layer built on top of Ray, the distributed computing framework. Ray handles cluster management, distributed scheduling, and actor-based concurrency. Ray Serve adds HTTP routing, request batching, health checks, and model pipeline composition on top of Ray's execution engine. You can run Ray Serve on a single machine or scale to a 100-node cluster with the same API." },
  { question: "How does Ray Serve compare to Kubernetes-native serving?", answer: "Ray Serve handles both the compute cluster management (via Ray) and the serving framework in one system. With Kubernetes-native approaches, you manage pods separately from the serving logic. Ray Serve is better when you already use Ray for training/data processing and want a unified cluster. Kubernetes is better when you need infrastructure-level isolation, compliance controls, or have a heterogeneous workload beyond ML serving." },
  { question: "What is a Ray Serve deployment and how does it scale?", answer: "A Deployment is a Ray Serve unit of compute — a Python class or function bound to HTTP routes. You control replicas (number of concurrent instances), ray_actor_options (CPU/GPU allocation per replica), and autoscaling policies. Ray Serve's autoscaler monitors replica queue length and target_num_ongoing_requests_per_replica, then adds or removes replicas automatically." },
  { question: "How do I build a multi-model pipeline in Ray Serve?", answer: "Ray Serve uses a Deployment Graph where deployments can call each other as handles. A preprocessing deployment calls an embedding deployment which calls a reranking deployment — all chained with async calls. The HTTP ingress deployment is the entry point, and Ray manages the routing and data transfer between deployments automatically." },
  { question: "How does GPU allocation work in Ray Serve?", answer: "Set num_gpus in ray_actor_options to allocate GPUs per replica. With fractional GPU allocation (num_gpus=0.5), multiple replicas can share a single physical GPU, increasing utilization for small models. Ray Serve respects CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES and supports multi-GPU models via num_gpus=2 or more. Use placement groups for fine-grained co-location control." },
  { question: "Can Ray Serve handle streaming responses?", answer: "Yes. Ray Serve supports streaming via generator-based handlers. Your handle method can yield chunks, and Ray Serve streams the response to the client with Server-Sent Events (SSE) or chunked transfer encoding. This is essential for LLM token streaming — each token generated by the model is yielded and immediately sent to the client, enabling low time-to-first-token." },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Ray Serve: Scalable ML Model Serving & Online Inference"
  description="Complete Ray Serve guide: @serve.deployment decorator, replica scaling config, model composition pipeline DAG, GPU allocation, HTTP ingress, and Ray Serve vs BentoML vs Triton comparison."
